        life mind & body C4 THE STRAITS TIMES MONDAY, AUGUST 31, 2020 | | | By JUSTIN CHUA example, if you are the type to enjoy a greasy burger every once in a while, fret not, because that would still be feasible. But maybe try squeezing in a healthier option to counter the occasional indulgence. Going cold turkey is hardly ever going to be a sustainabl­e approach. It is all about committing to a practical model of gradual progressio­n. If your fast food meals are only deemed worthy of consumptio­n when upsized, try going down the regular sized route for a change. Are you the Double McSpicy type? Try taking your indulgence­s down a patty. very day is another battle against the bulge, another opportunit­y to show your co-workers that the fitbit you privately work your wardrobe around is more than just a fashion piece. When people talk about how machines are slowly taking over our lives, they usually refer to perpetrato­rs like mobile devices and computers. But maybe too little scrutiny is afforded to their older cousin, and the way we let it dictate our daily routine — everything from what we wear, to what we eat. Weight-watching does not necessaril­y require drastic measures. Often, small actions done right can do the trick just as well. Moderation is key. For If you are the type to skip meals, there are other ways to curb the calories without having to endure excruciati­ng abdominal distension. You may revert to having the desired number of meals, only in smaller portions. So as much as the flashing digits on a plastic board may be associated with an impending need to shed the pounds, it does not mean a complete overhaul of your lifestyle is required. Unless, of course, you tend to pair your red fitbit with a glaring green top. Photos: GettyImage­s wellness specialist aesthetic SHERWOOD AESTHETICS MEDICAL CLINIC Skin Science & Wellness Concerns: acne, scars, pores, pigmentati­on, wrinkles, sagging, hair loss. Treatments: Q switch, yellow laser, botox, fillers, Re